<div class="recipe">
<p>Biscotti are the twice baked Italian cookie that you'll find in any coffee shop. For some reason, these cookies have the reputation as being quite hard to make. But today, we will show you how false that notion is. Sure, the second bake adds a little more time to a more basic cookie recipe, but the technical skill remains quit easy.</p>
<p>Many biscotti recipes will yield a cookie that will shatter your teeth if you do not first soak them in your cup of coffee. However, this recipe will give you a more forgiving texture, that is still very crispy, but is brittle enough to give way before your teeth do.</p>
<p>This recipe can be modified to add any mix-ins that you want! Do you have a near empty package of chocolate chips, or nuts that you do not know what to do with? Perfect! Just throw it in to these cookies and it will turn out great. Today, we will highlight a chocolate pecan flavour as well as a white chocolate, almond, and cranberry one. Feel free to change the mix-ins to anything. This recipe will make 2 "loaves", and each "loaf" can take about 2/3 cup to 1 cup of mix-ins, plus more for on top.</p>   
<p>The trickiest part of this recipe comes after the first bake, when you are getting ready to cut it into individual biscotti pieces. The key is to let the loaf cool COMPLETELY, and to not overbake the loaf during the first bake. As the loaf cools, it will firm up and become less crumbly.</p>
<p>It can be difficult to tell when the cookies are done during their cooking during their second bake. They should still have a slight bounce, but should still feel very firm when pressed. They will continue to firm up as they cool, so take care not to overbake them.</p>
